My previous estimate does not take into account errors in simulation.  What would be the air quality like in the next 9 days in Dubai? On 22 Mar, I visited https://www.iqair.com/united-arab-emirates/dubai and obtained 47 more hourly values from 20 Mar 8pm to 22 Mar 6pm.
Distribution is as follows: <85	11	23.40%	23.24%
85<=X<=95	9	19.15%	17.37%
95<X<105	5	10.64%	9.39%
105<=X<=115	12	25.53%	16.67%
>115	10	21.28%	33.33% This showed that the past 14 months’ probabilities (last column) are a somewhat close estimate to the past 47 hours probabilities (last 2nd column).
The average of the 47 values are 107. Question: What is the probability that the monthly average air quality will drop to the 95<X<105 range in the next 9 days in Dubai? So if the average air quality in the past 22 days is 107, in order for the air quality to drop to 104.9 overall in all of 31 days, the average air quality has to be (104.9*31 - 107*22)/9 = 99.8 for the next 9 days. From 28 Mar onwards, the next 4 days are Dubai’s spring break for schools. In 2021, 28-31 Mar’s 4-day average is 88, compared to whole month’s 100.
If we assume  a 12 point drop for 2022 in the last 4 days of March 2022 from 107, that makes the average of last 4 days to be 95. So if taking the average of 107*5 + 95*4, we get 101.6.
This is pretty close to 99.8, the required estimate to bring down the average down to the 95<X<105 range. 
I estimate the probability of average being 95<X<105 to be 40%. Hence, it’s 40-60.

As of today, 51.6% of the datapoints have been released. The average is 111, and I estimated (based on analyzing scenarios for low and high values) that it is likely that the average for the months will be around 113. Basically following the same ideas as @JoePeirson . Hence, I am adjusting accordingly.

Currently, and for some more days, the UAE and Dubai are under the influence of a stable high pressure area located on the Arabian peninsular, which means relatively pure and clean air due to winds from North-Western directions at low wind speeds, where the Persian Gulf obviously has some purifying function. As a result, the PM2.5 dust content as of now (88) is much lower than e.g. in Sarajevo (106) let alone in Algiers (152) or Kuwait City (169). There seems to be a pattern in which the AQI varies widely between roughly 75 and 125 under normal conditions within 24 hours, which suggests a 1-day-average may lie near 100, while traffic apparently worsens air quality during office hours on some particular days. The most important parameter, however, appears to be current weatherand thus of natural origin: wind directions and dust (sand) content of the air due to sand storm. Dubai in particular seems to benefit from it geology and from being located directly on the Persian Gulf's shores.
Unless strong sand storms take place before the end of March, it appears that March 2022 has been a mediocre month wrt to air quality so far, and will produce an "average" monthly AQI for the whole month.
One large source of uncertainty, however, is the fact that now and then values are not logged or temporarily unattainable. If there is a "systematic error", which excludes e.g. only very high or only very low values from being logged, the monthly average could be skewed slightly or biased. However, for Dubai's reporting, such "invalid entries" appear to be rare and reporting appears to be very stable.

Taking into account that it looks like we're on an upward trend. If avg for the remaining days is between 100 and 119 then March's final avg will go between 105-115. After exploring @mattlerner 's careful updates. I think it is sensible to state that the answer will most likely lie between 95.00 and 115.00. Today is the 13th day of March, and the average for the month is 105.62 so far. It would take rather extreme values for the average for the rest of the month to tip the balance out of the interval I suggested before (around 85 for the lower end and around 120 for the higher end). However, determining the right  bin at this point remains so difficult since the limit is precisely 105! I was tempted to say it's a 50/50 bet. I tried calculating the average for February 2020 (99.23) and that is higher than the average for March 2020 (94.58). On the other hand, the average for February 2021 (93.92) is lower than the average for March 2021 (100.49). And the average for February 2022 was 108.80. So I guess -and weather conditions are always volatile- this information is not really useful for prediction. I finally decided to assign a higher probability to the lower interval, hoping for some sort of regression to the mean. Though it will be very interesting to recalculate after the end of next week.
Excel s/s calculated average so far - 3/1/22 thru 3/5/22 - for Dubai "2022 PM2.5 MTD" AQI (https://www.airnow.gov/international/us-embassies-and-consulates/#UAE$Dubai, Historical tab), is 96.9
On reflection, in "normal" years AQI increases towards the end of the month.

Adjusting a bit now- in previous years the AQI in the first few days of March has hovered around the recent average - 96. But it's never fallen (through the rest of the month) to less than 83, which is what it would need to be at in order to fall in that bucket. So I'll give it 1%. It would need to be below 95 for the rest of the month in order to end up in the 85-95 bucket, which it has been once, but just barely, so I'll update down a bit. It would need to be below 107 to stay below 105- seems like there's an excellent chance of that happening. Still, I think there's a nonzero chance it'll bump up above 107 to end up in that 105-115 bucket - according to history, a roughly 25% chance across those top two buckets.
